<TEXT>
hurricane jerry swept ashore at texas galveston island on 
sunday spawning tornadoes and heavy rains and severe 
thunderstorms battered parts of michigan with high wind and large 
hail 
hurricane warnings and tornado watches were posted over 
southwestern louisiana and southeastern texas and people were urged 
to move inland from lowlying areas to avoid high tides and heavy 
rain 
the hurricane blew down power lines and trees and tossed cars in 
galveston before weakening overland but there were no immediate 
reports of injuries 
tornadoes were reported on the island in webster between 
houston and galveston and in orange where several homes and 
businesses were damaged there were no reports of injuries 
thunderstorms developed along and north of a warm front that 
extended across central lower michigan two campers at traverse 
city state park were injured when a tree fell on their trailer 
a tornado touched down near buckley mich but no injuries were 
reported said sgt marty dahlstrom of the wexford county sheriffs 
department numerous trees were knocked down at least one roof was 
ripped off and a mobile home was demolished dahlstrom said 
storms also produced wind gusts to 58 mph blowing down some 
trees and produced hail the size of golf balls the national 
weather service said 
elsewhere showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered along 
the gulf coast and the southern atlantic coast 
showers were scattered from the colorado rockies to south 
dakota with light rain and snow showers over wyoming and 
southcentral montana 
during the early morning dense fog was reported in eastern 
pennsylvania kentucky tennessee mississippi and the washington 
dc area 
roanoke va posted a record high of 85 degrees 
but in the northeast portland maine had a record low of 36 
and in the northwest eugene ore tied its record of 32 
sundays low for the lower 48 states was 22 degrees at allagash 
maine 
on saturday thunderstorms produced severe weather in new york 
state knocking out power to thousands of homes and killing at 
least one person a man whose mobile home was thrown several 
hundred feet 
a sky diver who was aloft over western new york when the storm 
hit was blown upward 1500 feet in three seconds said niagara 
county sheriffs deputy duane jacobs 
david konstabel said he had to cut his main parachute away to 
descend then use his reserve chute to land said skydiving 
instructor henry szczepanski 
