<TEXT>
the solar maximum satellite 
repaired in a daring space shuttle mission five years ago is 
expected to come crashing back to earth next month possibly in 
three big chunks 
the satellites imminent demise comes as the national 
aeronautics and space administration is trying to reassure the 
public about the safety of a nuclearpowered probe to be launched 
tuesday from the space shuttle atlantis 
charles redmond spokesman for nasas science office said the 
chances of satellite debris hurting anyone are remote because solar 
maxs track takes it over large expanses of ocean and sparsely 
settled land areas 
this is a routine satellite reentry redmond said sunday 
only the largest parts of the satellite are expected to survive the 
heat created by crashing through the atmosphere a gyroscope 
package that orients the satellite a frame for a sun sensor and a 
device that holds parts in place 
redmond said the satellite will hit the earth sometime in 
midnovember producing up to three 120pound pieces 
environmental activists oppose tuesdays shuttle launch saying 
an accident might release radioactive fuel over parts of florida 
the galileo probe carrying 494 pounds of plutonium238 is to 
be released by the five astronauts six hours after launch and sent 
on its sixyear journey to jupiter 
the only portions of the united states under the solar max 
ground track are south florida the extreme southern part of texas 
and hawaii the track also covers much of south america africa 
india australia and the southernmost tip of china 
solar max cost 77 million to build and launch in february 1980 
at a time of maximum activity in the suns 11year sunspot cycle 
its mission was to study solar flares 
but after 10 months of service three fuses blew in a control 
box and it was unable to point itself accurately that in turn 
caused four of its seven onboard instruments to fail 
in 1984 the shuttle challenger pulled alongside the satellite 
and astronaut terry hart grabbed it with the ships 50foot robot 
arm at the time it was called the historic first capture of a 
satellite in orbit for inflight repair and thenpresident reagan 
congratulated the astronauts in an oval officetochallenger call 
the following day two astronauts working in the open cargo 
bay replaced the satellites control system module and an 
electronics box 
solar max has been working well since then plans were made for 
a time to boost it to a higher orbit again but that would have set 
back other scheduled missions and the idea was abandoned redmond 
said 
its seen a complete solar cycle he said of the satellite 
essentially its completed its mission 
</TEXT>
