the supreme court today agreed to consider 
reinstating the drunkendriving conviction of a pennsylvania man 
who was videotaped answering police questions about his height 
weight and color of his eyes 
the court said it will decide whether police violated the 
motorists rights when they videotaped his responses before warning 
him of his right to remain silent or have a lawyer present 
inocencio muniz first was questioned by upper allen township 
patrolman david spotts who noticed munizs car stopped by the side 
of the road nov 30 1986 with the engine running 
the patrolman said he smelled alcohol on munizs breath and 
noticed that his eyes were glazed and bloodshot spotts said he 
told muniz not to drive until he was in a condition to operate the 
car safely but muniz drove off as the officer returned to his 
patrol car 
spotts pursued muniz ordered him to stop and told him to 
perform some sobriety tests which he failed the officer said he 
then took muniz to a police station where the motorist was 
videotaped answering questions about his height weight eye color 
and other personal characteristics 
only after those responses was muniz given socalled miranda 
warnings about his rights 
muniz convicted previously of drunken driving was convicted 
again and sentenced to a prison term of 45 days to 23 months 
a pennsylvania appeals court threw out the conviction last year 
it said any testimonial or communicative statements elicited 
from muniz following his arrest and before he received his miranda 
warnings should have been suppressed for trial purposes unless he 
effectuated a voluntary knowing and intelligent waiver of his 
rights 
the statistical questions muniz was asked were designed to 
reveal his thought processes and munizs confusion and failure 
to speak clearly indicated a state of drunkenness the state 
court said 
the case is pennsylvania vs muniz 89213 
