the bush administration plans to extend a 
19monthold ban on federal funding for research using fetal 
tissue the new york times reported today 
james mason assistant secretary for health in the department of 
health and human services has recommended to hhs secretary louis 
sullivan that the ban be continued over the objections of two 
federal panels the newspaper said 
sullivan was expected to act within a week said the times 
which cited no sources for its information 
spokesmen for sullivan and mason would say only today that issue 
was under review in the department 
abortion opponents have strongly opposed using fetal tissue for 
medical research though scientists say transplanting fetal tissue 
into adults may be effective in treating diabetes and parkinsons 
disease 
hhs imposed the ban in march 1988 while the department reviewed 
the issue in december two panels at the national institutes of 
health studied the question and voted to recommend that the ban be 
lifted 
the times quoted robert windom assistant secretary for health 
in the reagan administration as saying that he had been prepared 
to approve fetal tissue experiments in january but was instructed 
by thenhhs secretary otis bowen to leave the decision to the bush 
administration 
