<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to provide some 
guidelines for penalizing lawyers who file improper lawsuits 
the court said it will hear an appeal by a washington dc law 
firm penalized 21402 for filing an antitrust suit based on 
inadequate research 
the fine was ordered against cooter amp gell which represented 
dashs designer a nowbankrupt discount mens clothing store 
dashs filed an antitrust suit against hartmarx corp 
manufacturers and distributors of hickeyfreeman and hart 
schaffner amp marx mens clothing 
dashs said hartmarx illegally sold the brands exclusively to 
only one retailer in each of various major cities nationwide 
cooter amp gell filed a second suit after a secretary at the law 
firm telephoned some retailers in washington and three other cities 
to determine whether hartmarx had such an exclusivity policy 
hartmarx later asked for dismissal of the cooter amp gell suit 
after submitting affidavits that it distributed to as many as 20 
different retailers in some markets 
the law firm agreed to drop the suit 
the us circuit court of appeals here ordered the 21402 
penalty against cooter amp gell last may 
the appeals court said cooter amp gell claimed a nationwide 
conspiracy after polling merchants in only four eastern cities 
cooter amp gell had not made an inquiry reasonably commensurate with 
the extent of their allegations 
the supreme court said today it will decide whether the appeals 
court had authority to impose the fine after the lawsuit was 
withdrawn voluntarily the justices also will determine whether the 
appeals court used the right test to decide the law firm acted 
improperly 
the case is cooter amp gell vs hartmarx corp 89275 
</TEXT>
