<TEXT>
the governments attempt to suppress independent 
suppliers and restore monopoly control over distribution of farm 
supplies and equipment have caused major disruptions in the market 
an official daily said monday 
the government decision this year to reassert control over farm 
materials has aggravated the shortage reduced production 
blocked transfer between provinces created official speculation 
and furthered price hikes the china daily said 
the daily citing a survey taken by the beijingbased newspaper 
economic information said producers of fertilizer pesticides and 
plastic sheeting are going broke because of low stateset prices 
for their goods while high markups on products then sold by the 
state are arousing resentment of producers and consumers 
the government moved last year to restore central controls over 
agriculture and industry to counter rising prices and profiteering 
that have accompanied economic reforms under which commodity value 
is to some extent determined by market forces 
requirements that producers must sell to state monopoly 
departments rather than directly to farmers have led to delays and 
economic losses the report said 
in the central province of anhui 60 percent of fertilizer 
factories lost money in the first quarter of 1989 overall 52 of 
the countrys 91 factories making plastic sheeting halted 
operations and another 21 reduced production because of low prices 
and delayed payment from the state 
both stockpiling and supply shortages have occurred because some 
state offices to protect local interests have imposed 
restrictions on selling materials to other provinces 
some government companies taking advantage of the monopoly 
have speculated in hardtoget materials the state price bureau 
found that 95 percent of illegal price rises during a threemonth 
period this spring were done by state monopoly companies 
prices of agricultural materials were up 238 percent in the 
first quarter of the year and sales declined 
grain production has stagnated for four straight years largely 
because farmers put off by rising costs and low statedetermined 
prices for their crops have switched to other cash crops or gone 
into sideline businesses 
one major problem apparently unresolved has been a 
doubletrack pricing system where some materials are sold by the 
state at low prices and others are available on the free markets at 
usually much higher prices 
the system has led to widespread corruption with producers and 
officials diverting fertilizer seeds and other goods from state 
channels and forcing farmers to turn to the free markets 
</TEXT>
