<TEXT>
business sales far outpaced inventory 
accumulation in august the government said monday in a report that 
one analyst attributed to a miniinventory correction 
the commerce department said inventories edged up 03 percent to 
a seasonally adjusted 7899 billion while sales advanced a steep 
31 percent to 5268 billion the pace in inventories was down 
from a 09 percent hike in july while sales rose from a 09 decline 
the previous month 
the combination of sales advancing far faster than the 
accumulation of goods on shelves and backlots is good news for the 
economy if inventories were to pile up excessively it could mean 
cutbacks in production and a loss of jobs 
basically the inventories do not appear to show any signs of 
vulnerability said robert g dederick chief economist for the 
northern trust co of chicago 
ive been impressed by how managements have been keeping 
inventories from getting seriously out of hand he said 
the commerce report showed a decrease in the ratio of 
inventories to sales from 154 in july to 150 in august that 
means it would take one and a half months to exhaust inventories at 
the august pace 
manufacturers inventories which represent about 45 percent of 
the total were up only 03 percent while wholesalers backlogs 
actually dropped 01 percent 
retailers inventories however rose 07 percent which 
economist michael p niemira of mitsubishi bank in new york 
attributed in large part to a 16 percent advance in automobiles 
niemira described the slowing pace of inventory growth as a 
miniinventory correction that began last year in manufacturing 
and has been working its way through the other sectors 
manufacturers sales on the other hand rose 56 percent 
followed by wholesalers up 15 percent retailers sales gained 
07 percent 
overall both inventories and sales were 71 percent above those 
of august 1988 
