<TEXT>
the navy said monday it suspended a california 
defense contractor from doing business with the government saying 
the company supplied untested circuit boards for tactical missiles 
if flawed the suspect boards could keep the missiles from going 
off 
the boards made by asher engineering corp of baldwin park 
calif went into the navys phoenix longrange airtoair missile 
the harpoon antiship missile the harm antiradar missile 
tomahawk cruise missile sidewinder heatseeking missile sparrow 
radardirected missile and the advanced mediumrange airtoair 
missile the statement said 
the action was taken against asher because it did not keep 
adequate records of tests to see whether the boards met contract 
specifications the navy said in a statement issued at the pentagon 
the firm made printed wiring boards that were put into arming 
switches made by another defense contractor micronics 
international of brea calif 
micronics was the sole source of the arming devices for such 
vital missiles as the phoenix and the amraam or advanced 
mediumrange airtoair missile 
last month the pentagon said it had cut off all purchases of 
the items from micronics resulting in a delay in the deployment of 
some missiles and forcing the navy to take parts from old missiles 
until a new supplier begins production 
because of the problems with the parts the pentagon said last 
month that deployment of new phoenix missiles to the navys fleet 
would have to be delayed and cause delays in testing the amraam 
aboard navy f18 and air force f15 fighters until new parts were 
secured from another source 
but the service insisted that it had a full inventory of 
missiles for its operational forces to compensate for an expected 
stop in deliveries of the safety and arming device 
the devices will be produced by raymond engineering in 
massachusetts starting in 1991 
and the navy said problems with the boards had not been found to 
cause any detrimental missile performance 
the suspension is temporary pending the outcome of an 
investigation and any resulting legal proceedings the navy said 
although the boards did not meet contract specficiations 
missile components were tested at other levels when they were built 
into the full missile the navy said 
the action against asher was taken based on adequate evidence 
that this company and these individuals defrauded the government in 
performing subcontracts to manufacture printed wiring boards the 
statement said 
the navy said asher engineering badhadursinh asher jayant 
hathi and james menzies would be barred from contracting with any 
agency of the government for the temporary period 
each of the individuals named signed certificates saying the 
wiring boards were manufactured in accordance with the contract 
specifications 
however the statement said investigation shows that asher 
engineering does not have the capability to perform the required 
tests inhouse and there is no evidence that outside test 
facilities were utilized 
the arming device roughly comparable to the safety on a gun is 
built into the missiles fuze to prevent premature firing of the 
missile it also prevents explosions in accidents such as dropping 
a warhead on a carrier deck but allows the warhead to explode when 
it hits a target after being fired 
