capitol police arrested 55 protesters monday 
after they blocked the entrance to a house office building 
disrupted a house session and staged demonstrations in two 
congressional offices to protest us military aid to el salvador 
about 200 demonstrators rallied outside the capitol then 
marched to the rayburn house office building carrying banners 
denouncing rightwing death squads and us aid to el salvador 
fortyfour of the demonstrators then stationed themselves in 
front of one entrance to the building and chanted 70000 dead 
no more us out of el salvador until they were surrounded by 
police and arrested 
one protestor sustained a bloody nose during the arrests but 
there were no other injuries said capitol police spokesman dan 
nichols 
at about the same time two other small groups of demonstrators 
disrupted the offices of sen christopher dodd dconn and rep 
stephen solarz dny by chanting and reading in loud voices 
four protesters were arrested in each office nichols said neither 
lawmaker was present during the protests 
and later three demonstrators began chanting in the house 
visitors gallery during a vote republican lawmakers cheered when 
capitol police dragged them from the gallery 
the protests were sponsored by the committee in solidarity with 
the people of el salvador which opposes the central american 
countrys rightist government and supports the leftist farabundo 
marti liberation front rebels 
the action coincided with the opening of talks in san jose 
costa rica aimed at arranging a ceasefire in el salvadors 
decadelong civil war 
a foreign aid bill that includes 85 million in military aid to 
el salvador is scheduled to go to a housesenate conference 
committee as early as this week 
supporters of the aid contend that it is needed to demonstrate 
us confidence in alfredo cristiani newly elected president of 
the rightist arena party opponents say conditions should be placed 
on the aid to ensure that activities of rightwing death squads are 
curtailed 
