<TEXT>
members of congress who sided consistently 
against a strong clean air bill during a recent series of committee 
votes each received on average 73430 in campaign contributions 
from groups opposed to the legislation an advocacy group said 
monday 
the public interest research group which frequently supports 
environmental groups said those contributions were nearly four 
times as great as the average contributed by the same organizations 
19765 to members who voted consistently for toughening the 
proposed bill 
the environmental group said it compared a series of five key 
votes on the clean air legislation in the house health and 
environment subcommittee with campaign contributions to 
subcommittee members over the last eight years the contributions 
were from political action committees or pacs representing 
interests that have lobbied against strong clean air legislation 
the subcommittee last week unanimously approved a clean air 
bill but only after a number of close votes on amendments dealing 
with critical details of the bill the legislation has yet to be 
considered on the house floor 
according to the pirg analysis 11 members of the subcommittees 
who voted against proenvironmental positions on five amendments 
each received an average of 73430 in contributions from the pacs 
examined the nine congressmen who in each case voted in favor of 
proenvironmental positions received on average 19765 from the 
same pacs said the pirg 
among the subcommittee members those receiving the largest 
amount of money from the pacs examined were rep ralph hall 
dtexas 143000 rep john dingell dmich 134195 and rep 
jack fields rtexas 121755 
hall and fields were sponsors of prooil industry amendments to 
the clean air bill they and dingell were key in pushing through 
the subcommittee an amendment that scuttled by a 1210 vote a 
provision that would require automakers to build up to 1 million 
alternativefueled cars by 1997 
the auto and oil industries had lobbied against the 
alternativefueled cars provision 
at the same time rep henry waxman dcalif sponsor of a 
series of amendments aimed at strengthening the legislation 
received 8600 in contributions over the eight years from the same 
pacs the environmental group said 
the contributions were reported to the federal election 
commission by more than 60 pacs representing interests including 
the national automobile dealers association the big three 
automakers oil and coal companies electric utilities and the 
chemical industry 
