protect childrens rights said rhode islands department for 
children and their families promised to add 45 beds in foster homes 
and group programs by june 30 and to spend 1 million to add 45 
more by jan 31 1991 
us district judge raymond j pettine said he would decide 
within three days whether to accept the agreement dambra said the 
department acted in good faith and she believed it would try to 
adhere to the agreement 
the agreement would end dambras quest for a contempt citation 
against department director joseph j picano who did not meet a 
july 15 deadline to end most nighttonight placement to settle the 
child advocates 1986 lawsuit against the department 
the department now has agreed to shuffle children on a 
nighttonight basis for no more than three consecutive nights by 
nov 30 and eliminate any nighttonight placement by june 30 
except for emergencies 
the state pays foster homes and other facilities 20 per night 
per child beyond the their licensed capacity dambra said 
it was easy for them she said but the children had to 
leave every morning and fend for themselves at various day programs 
before finding out where they would sleep the next night they do 
not go to school dambra said 
theyre carrying their clothes around in trashbags and they 
are certainly not in a postion to receive counseling said 
dambra the routine wears them down to the point of hopelessness 
in many cases 
