south korea and north korea reached 
tentative agreement monday to allow visits between divided families 
for only the second time since 1945 but they remained divided on 
conditions for the exchanges 
the two sides meeting at red cross talks agreed to allow 300 
people from each nation to visit their relatives dec 8 they 
failed to agree on how long the visits would last or where visitors 
would be allowed to go 
the nations also failed to agree on terms for an exchange of 
artists and entertainers as part of the family visits both sides 
agreed to meet again at panmunjom nov 8 to try to iron out details 
the tentative breakthrough came after months of stalemate in 
various talks on easing tension the agreement could collapse if 
the two sides fail to resolve the differences 
the nations divided in 1945 have only once allowed visits by 
divided families when 50 people from each side were allowed to 
visit relatives for three days before returning home in 1985 
north korea and south korea are bitter rivals that have clashed 
frequently over the years the border is sealed and more than 10 
million divided relatives on both sides are unable to have any 
contact 
both sides said in separate news conferences that they also 
tentatively decided to hold a red cross conference on the reunion 
of separated families in north koreas capital of pyongyang on dec 
15 
song youngdae chief south korean delegate and his north 
korean counterpart park young soo acknolwedged the proposed 
exchange visits and red cross meeting wouldnt take place unless 
remaining problems are solved 
neverthless song said the agreement represented some 
progress 
i think a compromise might be possible if both sides negotiate 
on the principle of mutual concession song said 
when asked about prospects for a final agreement park said 
lets wait and see until how it comes out at the next session 
song said north korea insisted on sending 300 relatives and 300 
artists and entertainers while south korea had stuck to its 
position of each side sending 300 relatives and 50 entertainers 
the two sides also disagreed on how long the visits would last 
south korea proposed relatives be permitted to visit their 
hometowns in the north but north korean delegates refused saying 
the visits must be confined to seoul and pyongyang 
park said the south korean request was unrealistic because there 
was no guarantee that visiting south koreans would still find 
relatives in their hometowns 
park said north korea wanted to send more art performers as a 
symbolic gesture on the occasion of the second exchange of 
relatives the two sides exchanged 50 artists in the 1985 visit by 
relatives 
south korea said emphasis should be on the relative exchanges 
with the performers remaining a secondary matter some south korean 
officials say north korea wants to send entertainers to perform 
communist propaganda 
