<TEXT>
the justice department urged the supreme court 
on monday to uphold a missouri decision barring doctors from 
shutting off a lifesupport system for a severely braindamaged 
woman 
siding with the state of missouri in the first rightdodie 
case before the high court the department argued that the parents 
of nancy cruzan 31 did not have a right to stop their daughters 
treatment without a court order 
the justice department urged the high court to uphold a 43 
decision of the missouri supreme court that barred joe and joyce 
cruzan from allowing doctors to remove a feeding tube surgically 
implanted in their daughters stomach 
ms cruzan who breathes normally and has periods of 
wakefulness is kept alive by feedings through the tube doctors 
say that ms cruzan is incapable of interacting with her 
environment and has no thoughts or emotions 
a mentally competent adult may have a right to refuse or end 
treatment but the decision to withdraw lifesupport systems cannot 
be left to guardians acting on behalf of a person unable to express 
a choice the justice department said 
there is no basis for concluding that petitioners parents 
have a due process right to halt her treatment that is somehow 
independent of petitioners own desires the department said in a 
friendofthecourt brief 
whatever may be said about the rights of a currently competent 
adult an adult who is now incompetent cannot make an informed 
decision to refuse treatment and thus cannot be said to have a 
qualified fundamental right the justice department said in its 
brief submitted by solicitor general kenneth starr 
the justice department offered an argument that was at odds with 
the american medical association and other groups which joined the 
cruzans in urging the high court to allow withdrawal of the tube 
the department said the federal government has an interest in 
the case because it operates 443 hospitals and nursing homes where 
issues about termination of treatment arise on a continuing 
basis 
reasonable minds can differ on whether courts are best suited 
to determine an incompetent patients preferences but the 
missouri court applied reasonable rules in this case the brief 
argued 
the missouri court reasonably concluded that any error should 
be made on the side of life it continued 
in so doing however the court did not take an unreasonably 
rigid approach to the evidence of petitioners wishes 
the cruzans testified that at one point their daughter told them 
she would not want to be kept alive in a permanent coma but the 
missouri court did not accept their statement as deciding the issue 
in view of the states powerful interests in protecting 
incompetent persons against abuse an ensuring that any decision 
made in the past was wellconsidered state rules of evidence and 
procedure designed to give effect to previous decisions to refuse 
treatment should be upheld as long as they are reasonably 
designed to serve an important state interest the justice 
department said 
the department has argued that this standard should also be 
applied to laws that prohibit or restrict abortion the briefs 
discussion of privacy rights mirrored the position the justice 
department has taken on the abortion issue 
the department said the court should decline petitioners 
invitation to extend the right of privacy to cover all types of 
decisions about medical treatment and procedures 
