<TEXT>
a study shows that americas cities are 
starving for trees forestry experts said monday 
most cities in the united states could accommodate more than 
twice the number of trees that now line their streets said james 
kielbaso a forestry professor from michigan state university 
those cities are missing out on the cooling and energysaving 
benefits that trees provide he said 
kielbaso was one of the lead researchers in a recent study by 
the american forestry association which was released at the 
organizations fourth urban forest conference about 500 tree 
experts and activists attended the meeting 
if we double the number of trees in our cities we would in 
effect triple the environmental benefits of trees kielbaso said 
the study was compiled from the results of a random survey of 
street trees in about 300 communities in the united states 
kielbaso said 
there are an estimated 60 million street trees in the country 
kielbaso said there are an average of 78 street trees per mile he 
said spaced an average of 150 feet apart 
kielbaso said that decreasing the space between each tree to 50 
feet would allow for nearly 100 million new street trees 
a previous study found that street trees make up only onetenth 
of the urban forest in the nations cities he said yet they play 
an important role in providing shade and other benefits to city 
dwellers 
kielbaso said that among the conclusions of his study was that 
only half of 1 percent of city budgets are spent on trees 
underfunded tree maintenance programs and difficult growing 
conditions lead to early mortality rates for trees he said 
most street trees are small twothirds are under 12 inches in 
diameter and most medium to large trees are in fair to poor 
condition he said 
gary moll the afas vice president of urban forestry said that 
urban forests have been overlooked too often as ways to help slow 
global warming 
research is just now beginning to show the environmental and 
economic value of our urban forests moll said 
the afa has launched a citizens treeplanting campaign called 
global releaf which is aimed at getting 100 million trees planted 
in the nations communities by 1992 
</TEXT>
