<TEXT>
with its waters classified as 
biologically dead and its pacific beach turned a yellowgreen 
this former fishing community wants a small slice of chiles copper 
fortune to compensate for a shoreline buried in toxic sludge 
its not the first time chanarals 12700 inhabitants have 
played david to the goliath of the state copper mining corporation 
which is by far the countrys largest single company and producer 
of more than a third of chiles 8 billion in annual export 
earnings 
a year ago the chanaral citizens committee won a legal suit 
against the corporation known by the acronym codelco the supreme 
court ordered codelco to shut down a 100mile sluice that has 
carried millions of tons of waste westward from its massive el 
salvador mine in the andes to the pacific coast at chanaral 
such environmental victories are rare in latin america and the 
third world in general where governments trailing in the 
worldwide race for development generally give priority to 
industrial growth over damage to nature 
but ecological awareness and activism has begun taking root in 
latin america with new environmental and naturalist groups 
emerging and becoming increasingly vocal 
nowhere is that awareness more manifest than in chanaral 605 
miles north of santiago chiles capital 
the citizens committee is supported by a rainbow of local 
social groups and threw a rousing street party complete with a 
local rock band when the supreme courts ruling came down 
codelco was forced to start building another sluice from the el 
salvador pit to a remote uninhabitated plain on the desert that 
dominates northern chile the 135million project has run into 
delays but the company promises to complete it early next year 
with that legal victory under its belt the citizens are seeking 
more satisfaction 
the state must compensate us because the pollution buried our 
fishing maritime and port development for decades said julio 
palma a truck driver who was a leader in promoting the original 
suit 
in a new damage suit being planned the community will ask for 
the equivalent of one us cent for each pound of copper extracted 
from el salvador palma said the money will create a town 
development fund 
for the delays in building the new sluice which was supposed to 
be completed in april the citizens committee is asking 1 million 
in compensation 
in the existing sluices 51 years of operation 200 million to 
500 million tons of crushed rock and tainted water have been dumped 
onto chanarals shore palma said 
scientific studies used in the committees suit found waters and 
marine life around the community contaminated with dangerous levels 
of copper zinc molybdenum and arsenic which is used in 
extracting metal from ore 
as far back as 1975 a marine biologist rolf benhcke said in a 
study the chanaral beach is a biologically dead beach it 
has been impossible to detect a single living organism 
that same year the sluices mouth was moved from central 
chanaral to palitos cove five miles to the north but the 
communitys shore remains barren and a band of unnatural 
yellowgreen runs parallel to the water 
over the decades the waste piled up and pushed the shoreline out 
more than a mile buried in the process were commercial docks a 
threestory pier used by fishing boats and a shipwreck dating back 
to the 1940s that used to attract tourists residents said 
oldtimers like amanda venegas recall another era when there 
were so many fish that when we went bathing they swam between our 
legs 
nonetheless the community is proud of having successfully 
closed the sluice down and believe it could signal something for 
other third world countries 
the ruling is the most important in decades on ecological 
issues and creates a precedent for latin america said the 
citizens committees lawyer rafael asenjo 
he said ecology groups in the phillipines and peru have asked 
the committee for copies of the decision so has a group in canada 
although canada it is not part of the third world 
</TEXT>
