<TEXT>
when mo dafeng was a young boy he found 
himself attracted to what was a very precarious occupation in his 
native china he wanted to be like his father an artist and 
become a painter 
when i was probably 5 years old i liked drawing cars and the 
trains and the airplanes especially some american fighters he 
said 
but his father who had seen many of his artist friends banished 
to the countryside in 1957 because of their political views tried 
to channel his sons talent into other pursuits 
my father thought any son should not be an artist the 
32yearold mo recalled he thought i should be an architect 
mo however wasnt to be denied he studied oil painting and 
stage design at the peoples liberation army art institute in 
beijing eventually becoming an official army artist 
given his status in the army his early work was restricted to 
propaganda pieces and theater sets one of his assignments took him 
to the front lines of the border war between china and vietnam in 
1979 
if you want to become famous you have to paint history 
military paintings he said 
since leaving the army in 1983 hes used his canvas to capture 
scenes of personal significance riverfronts and cityscapes but 
never portraits the result is that mo is now considered by some 
collectors as one of the leading contemporary realism artists 
in china 
nine of his oil paintings are included in an exhibit of chinese 
contemporary realist paintings at the greenwich workshop inc 
gallery in the southport section of fairfield 
david p usher greenwich workshop president defined 
contemporary realism as paintings you can look at and you know 
what it is 
a total of 110 paintings from 30 chinese artists are included in 
the current show the paintings were selected from among 400 put on 
display earlier this year at the nanjing exhibition in china 
the paintings are bright bold and feature optimistic themes 
including landscapes portraits and posterstyle works that are 
markedly different from the traditional chinese ink and watercolor 
paintings done on rice paper 
i was amazed by the quality of the painting said usher who 
personally selected the pieces on exhibit during a visit to china 
when people think of chinese painting they think of birds 
bamboo and the mountains it was a little like andrew wyeth and 
norman rockwell going to china 
the contemporary realism style traces its roots to french 
academic realism and avantegarde styles and to the soviet style of 
socialist reform some of its more familiar examples are the huge 
patriotic or propaganda murals visible in major squares 
the exhibit is the second for greenwich workshop an art 
publishing firm it held an earlier exhibit of chinese paintings in 
november 1988 and had sales exceeding 250000 the exhibit also 
led to the introduction of limited edition prints which have sold 
well since their introduction this spring 
usher said his company is the only one in this country to 
maintain its ties with chinese artists many other firms severed 
their ties with the artists after the army crushed the student 
prodemocracy movement in beijings tiananmen square in june 
only one of the paintings in the current exhibit can be 
interpreted as making a statement on the tiananmen incident the 
painting by huang zhong yang shows a child releasing a dove from 
captivity 
we made the conscious effort to keep working with them 
usher said in all honesty i guess were a lifeline to the 
artists and if we stop doing what were doing there would be no 
exposure or market for their work 
the continuing relationship was made possible under an agreement 
usher reached in may with chinas cultural affairs ministry and the 
china artists association an elite organization representing about 
7000 artists the agreement established a network by which chinese 
art would pass through the greenwich workshop to about 1400 
dealers in the united states canada and britain 
both artists and the chinese government receive a share of the 
profits from sales said liu kuifang director of the china project 
for greenwich workshop 
the business connection is very important to chinese artists 
who while supported by the government dont learn how to market 
or exhibit their work abroad there is no market in china 
out of the 400 you could have put about 80 in any gallery in 
the world usher said 
mos contributions to the exhibit depict the river communities 
near his parents home his family lives in south china where mos 
father mo pu is the retired head of the hung zhou academy the 
countrys oldest art academy 
the color the river its very beautiful mo said 
landscape is one of my favorite objects if you want to find 
people to pose everyone is too busy 
mo who has been a professional artist since age 18 currently 
is a graduate student at the pratt institute in new york city 
where he is studying western art and artists he expects to 
complete his studies in about two years and then return to china to 
put his new skills into practice 
as artist in china its very hard they have knowledge but 
most artists know how to survive he said 
</TEXT>
