<TEXT>
ed tarangioli thrives on surprise 
looking at his blond hair and straight shoulders youd guess 
hes a wellpreserved 65 hes going on 81 but he saves his 
biggest surprises for tennis courts where after cancer and 
cataract operations he has reigned 
my kind of tennis is to do the unexpected tarangioli said 
during a chat at his victorian house on a treeshaded hillside in 
this new york suburb at this age youre not the powerful hitter 
you were but you play a very intelligent game you build up points 
almost like chess 
at the national level most of the players dont make mistakes 
theyve been playing for 50 60 years so you throw in as many 
surprises as you can the drop shot the lob the sudden serve and 
volley thats what works 
a top player also needs one great shot and his is the 
backhand drive 
the 5foot10 155pound tarangioli achieved no 1 ranking in 
both singles and doubles in the 80s age group after winning the 
national grass and indoor singles and three doubles tournaments 
with different partners in 1988 
rankings last one year the 1989 roster being based on 1988 
play so far this year tarangioli has lost in the finals of three 
national tournaments to jack staton of st petersburg fla whos 
playing for the first time in the division chances are staton will 
be no 1 and tarangioli no 2 in 1990 
thirtythree men hold us national rankings in the 80s division 
and 17 headed by kenneth beer of burlingame calif are ranked in 
the over85 group eightyeight names are listed in the 70s led by 
powell taylor of norfolk va 
the us tennis association strongly promotes the senior game 
organizing tournaments nationally and sectionally by fiveyear age 
increments seven women in the 75s hold national singles rankings 
for 1988 headed by liu shangku tao of san francisco stars of the 
past like bobby riggs gardnar mulloy tom brown and dorothy 
cheney are still playing 
tarangioli was a high school shortstop when he got into tennis 
with a friend who wanted someone to hit with the friend 
happened to be francis x shields then a national junior star 
later a toptenner they practiced on park courts where tarangioli 
recalls you brought your own net 
he learned fast going on to captain the new york university 
team and play three years in the national championships at forest 
hills his best performance was when he reached the finals of the 
new york metropolitan clay tournament in 1929 after defeating frank 
hunter ranked no 2 nationally jules seligson then beat him for 
the cup inscribed with illustrious names like bill tildens 
every player plays a tournament where he feels he cant miss a 
ball it looks so big tarangioli says that was mine 
after college and with no money in it tarangioli dropped 
out of tournament tennis got a law degree at nyu and became a wall 
street lawyer and teacher heading the law department of baruch 
college of the city university of new york for 30 years he met his 
wife harriet cullinan now dead at a tennis club in yonkers and 
they had two boys and two girls all good tennis players 
he returned to competitive tennis in his 40s reaching the 
finals of the national veterans indoor championship in new york in 
1956 i made history by losing he said because the winner was 
dr reginald weir the first time a black man had won a national 
championship a woman althea gibson won a us championship the 
following year and arthur ashe in 1968 
to keep in shape he does calisthenics 20 minutes a day and 
plays singles five times a week seven years ago he underwent 
surgery for colon cancer he also has had a prostate operation and 
cataracts removed from both eyes 
the great thing about supersenior tennis is that all these 
men have something to look forward to he said were very 
happy because we have goals ive won the 80s im very pleased 
with it i wanted to do it my next goal is i want to win the 85s 
</TEXT>
