but other german and some norwegian traders reported that while 
individual investors were dumping stocks institutions were holding 
back 
sharp price drops triggered european versions of circuit 
breakers market procedures designed to calm roiled markets 
and prompted some authorities to step in to contain the damage 
price drops of 15 percent triggered trading suspensions in many 
shares in paris brussels and lisbon 
a deluge of sell orders caused computer problems in brussels 
where there was little trading all session amsterdam also had 
computer problems during its session 
the frankfurt exchange and others stayed open late to compensate 
for the trading difficulties 
right now with the dollar up and wall street up it certainly 
doesnt look like any crash said a zurich dealer 
its all wall street right now an equities analyst with the 
london investment firm james capel and co said adding that new 
yorks performance after the european markets closed would set 
tuesdays tone for europe 
on wall street the dow jones average of 30 industrials which 
plummeted 190 points on friday fell sharply after its opening 
before bouncing higher and lower throughout the session the 
widelyfollowed market index finished up 8812 points at 265738 
fridays debacle in new york occurred after european centers had 
closed for the weekend and european investors were not reassured by 
a modest setback in tokyo earlier monday 
britains chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson issued a 
statement after a routine meeting with prime minister margaret 
thatcher saying mondays share price declines were not 
surprising 
he blamed the largely american phenomenon of junk bonds 
lowrated securities used widely to help finance the us corporate 
takeover wave for the slide 
lawson also said as the events of 1987 demonstrated there is 
no need for sharp fluctuations in the stock market to have 
significant effects on the real economy 
a spokesman for the west german central bank the bundesbank 
said were observing the situation very intensively weve been 
in constant contact with the affected countries he requested 
anonymity 
madrid stock exchange president pedro guerrero said the main 
challenge was to maintain liquidity at all costs and this has 
been achieved totally he described trading as frenetic but 
satisfactory 
