lin broadcasting corp said monday its board 
took no position on the latest buyout offer from mccaw cellular 
communications inc and requested more information about the 
proposal 
lin also asked bellsouth corp the atlantabased regional 
telephone company with whom it has reached a separate agreement to 
merge cellular telelphone operations what it thought of mccaws 
offer for control of lin 
kirkland washbased mccaw the nations largest cellular 
telephone company said last week it would offer 125 a share or 
275 billion for 22 million of lins 539 million shares 
together with the 51 million shares of lin it already owns 
successful completion of the offer would give mccaw control of lin 
with slightly more than 50 percent of shares outstanding 
under the new offer mccaw indicated it would either buy the 
rest of the companys stock in five years or put the company up for 
auction 
the proposal replaced an earlier buyout offer under which mccaw 
said it would pay 110 a share for the 90 percent of lin that it 
did not already own that valued all of lin at 59 billion 
lin the new yorkbased cellular telephone giant which also 
operates television stations and has a small publishing business 
rejected mccaws earlier offer as inadequate and reached the deal 
with bellsouth 
in mondays announcement lin said its board expects to take a 
position on the mccaw offer before it expires now scheduled for 
oct 27 
but lin said its board wanted to know more about the offer 
including whether mccaw is prepared to guarantee that those shares 
not covered by the new partial tender offer would have a value of 
at least 125 a share 
it also wanted an explanation of how mccaw can be sure other 
bidders will be willing to pay an appropriate price for lin if it 
decides not to buy the rest of the companys shares in five years 
and how it can be sure mccaw will not act in a manner in the next 
five years that would diminish lins value 
in its statement lin said bellsouth indicated that it would 
respond to mccaws proposal in as full and effective a manner as 
is warranted and is carefuly reviewing alternatives 
